### Background

We've developed a sophisticated dataset of \~250 (small but sufficient :) ) "[Living Off the Land](https://www.crowdstrike.com/en-us/cybersecurity-101/cyberattacks/living-off-the-land-attack/)" (LOTL) attack sequences that our current detection system struggles with. These attacks use legitimate Windows tools in malicious ways, making them nearly invisible to traditional rule-based detection.

**The Challenge**: Our customer successfully detects these attacks using `Claude-Sonnet-4.5`, achieving 94% accuracy. Their legacy regex- and rule-based detections achieved \<73% precision and recall on the same data. However, `Claude-Sonnet-4.5` costs them \~$0.0018 per alert to analyze (with millions of daily events, this is unsustainable for their operations). Your task is to build a faster, cheaper detector that captures the LLM's detection capability for their use case.

**Baseline**: Treat `Claude-Sonnet-4.5` as the reference detector for both performance and cost. Your solution should come close to its detection quality while being dramatically more efficient.
